Just tried this out, and found something interesting.

It seems that for some reason when using `T extends BaseEntity`, in cases where BaseEntity is a class, it seems that `FindOptionsWhereProperty<NonNullable<T["id"]>>` does not resolve to the equivalent `FindOptionsWhereProperty<NonNullable<string>>`. Not sure why this is the case, and if this is a limitation from typescript.

But this will work:
```typescript
export async function checkAuth<T extends {id: string}>(
  entity: T,
  repo?: Repository<T>,
): Promise<[T, boolean]> {
  let existingEntity: T | null

  let exists = false
  if (repo) {
    existingEntity = await repo.findOneBy({ id: entity.id }) // ok
```

It's also worth mentioning, even if this did work, it only gets part of the way there. Im my full implementation of `Base Entity` has other fields on it, so using this type of polymorphism is key.

```
export abstract class BaseEntity implements ObjectLiteral {
  abstract readonly id: string

  abstract getConfig(): { syncType: string }
  abstract getPermissionGroups(): Promise<string[]>
}
```

I'm having the same issue. I build find options first and then conditionally change it based on some things. Solved it for now by using BaseEntity first and then casting back to FindManyOptions
```ts
  private async getInstalls<T extends MyBaseEntity>(
    entity: new () => T,
    packageName: string,
    period: Period,
    from: Date,
  ): Promise<T[]> {
    const repo = this.manager.getRepository<T>(entity);

    const findOptions: FindManyOptions<MyBaseEntity> = { where: { packageName } };
    switch (period) {
      case Period.Day:
        findOptions.where = Object.assign(findOptions.where, { date: this.toDate(from) });
        break;
      // ...
    }

    return repo.find(findOptions as FindManyOptions<T>);
  }
```

